<HEADLINE>
<P>
POINDEXTER SENTENCED TO PRISON FOR ROLE IN IRAN-CONTRA SCANDAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thank you for your short but succinct editorial on the sentencing of John 
Poindexter ("Admiral Was Far Off Course," June 12). 
</P>
<P>
There was hope that this trial would raise the still unanswered questions of 
the Iran-Contra scandal and publicize how our institutions failed to get to the 
bottom of it. 
</P>
<P>
In the preceding trials of Oliver North, Richard Secord, Albert Hakim and 
Joseph Fernandez, claims of national security have been used to cover up 
criminal activity. Those who still consider these men as heroes seem to have 
forgotten that, as your editorial points out, the very foundation of American 
constitutionalism is shaken when the checks and balances are ignored. George 
McGovern has called Iran-Contra, "The greatest constitutional crisis since the 
Civil War." 
</P>
<P>
Now a little justice has been meted out but it leaves relatively untouched and 
unpunished the high-ranking government officials who have put themselves above 
the law by hiding from prosecution behind the cloak of national security. 
</P>
<P>
We can only hope that the non-government case still to be tried, the Christic 
Institute civil suit, will go forward. Its goal is a worthy one: to insure that 
the abuses committed in the Iran-Contra affair will be prevented in the future 
and that national security will once again become security for the nation 
rather than security from prosecution for those who commit crimes in the name 
of patriotism. 
</P>
<P>
PATRICIA S. CARMEL 
</P>
<P>
Rancho Santa Fe 
</P>
</TEXT>
