FIREFIGHTERS GET BIAS SETTLEMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Civic leaders have agreed to pay more than $500,000 to 13 black firefighters to 
settle claims that they suffered from racist attitudes and abuse during the 
1980s. 
</P>
<P>
The 13 charged they were the target of physical and verbal harassment by some 
white firefighters who hassled their black peers with gorilla noises and by 
posting abusive materials in lockers. "What's truly frightening is the failure 
of the fire administration at the time to intervene in these embarrassing 
incidents of racial harassment," county Supervisor Harry Britt said. The 
settlements, involving actions that occurred between 1981 and 1988, ranged from 
$10,000 to $85,000. 
