<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: MAN SENTENCED IN 1982 DRUNK-DRIVING DEATHS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A man who eluded police for eight years after causing a 1982 crash in Reseda 
that killed two women pleaded no contest Tuesday to manslaughter, drunk driving 
and other charges and agreed to a prison sentence of three years and eight 
months. 
</P>
<P>
Ruben Perez Lemon, 28, of Woodland Hills, entered the plea after prosecutors 
said they would not seek the maximum sentence for the charges -- four years and 
four months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
Sentencing is scheduled for July 12 in Van Nuys. 
</P>
<P>
Ruth Hanzlik of Granada Hills, the mother of one of the women killed, fought 
successfully after her daughter's death for tougher sentences for convicted 
drunk drivers. But the new sentences do not apply to Lemon because the crash 
occurred before they went into effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
