<HEADLINE>
<P>
PUBLISHER OF STRAPPED ENTREPRENEUR RESIGNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JONATHAN WEBER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
IRVINE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Entrepreneur Magazine publisher Clare N. Thain resigned last week, Entrepreneur 
Chairman Peter Shea said Tuesday, and his duties at the cash-strapped 
publication will be assumed by Shea and Associate Publisher James L. 
Fitzpatrick. 
</P>
<P>
Shea also said he had turned down a joint-venture deal with Omni Group, a New 
York-based publishing arm of the Swiss company Omni Holdings. He said talks 
were continuing with other possible overseas investors whom he declined to 
identify. 
</P>
<P>
Entrepreneur has also laid off six people, including three marketing employees 
and three clerical workers, Shea said. The company now employs 61 full-time 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
"I've gotten more involved in the day-to-day operations, and we looked at the 
overhead and decided we were a little top-heavy," Shea said in explaining 
Thain's departure. 
</P>
<P>
But Thain said Tuesday that he left because of a disagreement over "the 
direction the magazine was taking." He declined further comment. 
</P>
<P>
Shea said the cutbacks would not affect growth at Entrepreneur and the 
company's two other publications, New Business Opportunities and the recently 
launched Entrepreneurial Woman. 
</P>
<P>
Shea acknowledged earlier this month that fast-growing Entrepreneur had 
encountered some cash-flow problems and that it was late in paying more than $1 
million owed to three suppliers. But he denied that the cash pinch threatened 
the company's future. Shea said Tuesday that about $500,000 of the outstanding 
bills had been paid off in the last several weeks. "We're within 60 days on all 
our payments," he said. "Our creditors are happy." 
</P>
<P>
The creditors, including World Color Press of Los Angeles, Corinthian 
Communications of Corona del Mar and Horizon Paper Co. of New York, have 
declined comment on the situation. 
</P>
<P>
Although Shea has said that the company can continue to grow without a cash 
infusion from a partner, some analysts view the fact that he is in talks about 
possible joint ventures as an indication that the firm's problems are serious. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Clare N. Thain 
</P>
