<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
'HAVE TO BE PRESIDENT' -- WALESA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WARSAW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lech Walesa said in an interview today that he doesn't want to but "will have 
to be president" to preserve Poland's new democracy, and he vowed to wage a 
political war against his former Solidarity allies. 
</P>
<P>
The union leader challenged the longtime intellectual allies in Warsaw who are 
opposing him to start a separate "center-left" political party and not hide 
behind the broad label of Solidarity. 
</P>
<P>
"I do not want to be president. (But) I will have to be president," Walesa said 
in the interview in Gazeta Wyborcza, Poland's largest newspaper, whose use of 
the Solidarity logo Walesa disputes. 
</P>
<P>
Walesa announced that he plans to start a daily newspaper owned by the 
Solidarity union itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
